trådlös/lab-1/lab-1.html.description: #trådlös #lab #TODO/in-progress The first amplifier () have the most impact in reducing the Noise Ration (), since it is included in the numerator in every term in Friis formula.To select the wanted signal in a crowded signal space, reject mirror images -->Keep the low noise amplifier in the linear region at the cost of insertion loss.The mixer (with the help of the Lo freq) down samples the RF signal tot eh lower wanted frequency using the propertycos(A) × cos(B) = ½[cos(A - B) + cos(A + B)]We are interested int the difference signal, which we easily can get using a band-pass filter after the mixer.The incoming signal can vary greatly depending on the distance and other obstacles. The AGC keeps the strength of the signal at a constant level. The rest of the receiver can be built assuming the incoming signal keeps this level.Terms: A. The two-tone test.Sen in a signal composing of two signals with frequency very close to eachother. By looking at the output we can measure the intermodulation distortion of the system. Basically a measurement of how linear out system is. B. Sensitivity.minumum input signal neeed for the reciver to demodulate the signal. Often expressed in dBm. Determined by the circuts Noise Figure. Example: Noise Floor for a 200 kHz FM channel at room temperature: -121 dBm Receiver Noise Figure: 5 dB Required SNR for acceptable FM audio: 12 dB Sensitivity = -121 dBm + 5 dB + 12 dB = -104 dBm C. Selectivity.  Selectivity is a receiver's ability to distinguish a desired signal from unwanted signals at other frequencies. D. 1 dB compression.The 1 dB Compression Point is defined as the point where the actual gain is 1 dB less than the ideal small-signal gain. E. Intercept point.An Intercept Point (IP) is a theoretical point where the power of the undesired distortion products (from a non-linear device) would equal the power of the desired fundamental signals.NF calc:NF2_lin = 10^(2/10) = 1.585Better image rejection and better selectivity.

headers.heading: EITF51 - Circuits and Systems for Wireless Communication: Lab 1
1 Write the Friis formula and explain the importance of having a low noise amplifier connected to the antenna in the receiver chain.
2 In what sense a filter connected to the antenna is good for (filters have insertion loss)?
3 Explain the function of the mixer and oscillator. What are they used for in the receiver architectures?
4 Why do we need automatic gain control for the AM receiver?

info_showOrphanNodes.description: Show nodes that are not connected to any other nodes.

info_showAttachments.description: Show attachments like images and PDFs as nodes in the graph.

info_allowGlobalGraph.description: Allow the user to view the global graph of all nodes.

info_allowExpand.description: Allow the user to pop-out the graph view to take up the whole screen

info_attractionForce.description: How much should linked nodes attract each other? This will make the graph appear more clustered.

info_linkLength.description: How long should the links between nodes be? The shorter the links the more connected nodes will cluster together.

info_repulsionForce.description: How much should nodes repel each other? This will make disconnected parts more spread out.

info_centralForce.description: How much should nodes be attracted to the center? This will make the graph appear more dense and circular.

info_edgePruning.description: Edges with a length above this threshold will not be rendered, however they will still contribute to the simulation. This can help large tangled graphs look more organised. Hovering over a node will still display these links.

info_minNodeRadius.description: How small should the smallest nodes be? The smaller a node is the less it will attract other nodes.

info_maxNodeRadius.description: How large should the largest nodes be? Nodes are sized by how many links they have. The larger a node is the more it will attract other nodes. This can be used to create a good grouping around the most important nodes.
